Fix Additional Keyboard Interactivity Issues

04
On this page
  1. 🛠 Challenge: Update Submit Buttons on Home & About Pages
  2. 🛠 Solution: Updating the Submit Buttons
  3. Wrapping up the Keyboard Testing Module

Thanks to JavaScript, the user is able to Tab through the MegaNav options and toggle the menu open and shut.

The menu’s working with the keyboard, but there are still a couple of issues that need to be fixed.

🛠 Challenge: Update Submit Buttons on Home & About Pages

Both the Homepage and the About page have forms with div-based submit buttons.

Update the markup on both buttons to enable them to be keyboard focusable and operable.

Note that these interactive controls are meant to submit forms, not navigate the user.

🛠 Solution: Updating the Submit Buttons

On the homepage, the submit icon button is inside of a div with a class of form-submit.

Here’s what it looks like after updating the markup:

// Inside index.html
<div class="form-field form-submit">
	<button class="btn-submit btn-lookingglass" onclick="javascript: alert('Submitted!');">
		<span class="icon-lookingglass-white"></span>
	</button>
</div>
// Inside index.html
<div class="form-field form-submit">
	<button class="btn-submit btn-lookingglass" onclick="javascript: alert('Submitted!');">
		<span class="icon-lookingglass-white"></span>
	</button>
</div>

Over on the About page at about/index.html the submit button is also inside of a form-submit div. Here’s that markup update:

<div class="form-submit">
	<button class="btn-send">Send<span class="icon-arrow"></span></button>
</div>
<div class="form-submit">
	<button class="btn-send">Send<span class="icon-arrow"></span></button>
</div>

Wrapping up the Keyboard Testing Module

In this first section of the workshop, we moved from a navigation menu that could only be used when hovering with the mouse into something much more keyboard-friendly.

This demonstrates the amount of impact we can have on our application in such a short amount of time. It’s a reason why I really believe we can do more in our industry.

Accessibility can get complicated and can take a while depending on how a website or web application was built.

But ultimately, a lot of the things we see as barriers on the web are not that complicated to fix.

We can make quite a bit of progress by diving in and fixing stuff!

With every feature and Pull Request that comes in, chip away at making your application accessible by doing some keyboard testing.
